00:32:39.870 --> 00:32:44.560
you think of Eugene O'Neill, who
long days journey into night,

00:32:44.560 --> 00:32:48.550
he just hung onto it until the
protagonists were dead, right?

00:32:48.550 --> 00:32:51.730
I mean, he just, he wrote it
and then he just hung onto it.

00:32:51.730 --> 00:32:54.110
But there are other people

00:32:54.110 --> 00:32:58.810
who are much more comfortable just
having it out there come what may.

00:32:58.810 --> 00:33:01.650
So I think it's really
an individual--

00:33:01.650 --> 00:33:06.350
each person has to make
their peace with it.

00:33:06.350 --> 00:33:08.090
Thank you.

00:33:08.090 --> 00:33:09.660
&gt;&gt; Thank you for your discussion.

00:33:09.660 --> 00:33:10.960
It was interesting.

00:33:10.960 --> 00:33:15.650
How hard was it, or what was it
like going from a book about women

00:33:15.650 --> 00:33:19.450
in the middle of their
life, in that perspective,

00:33:19.450 --> 00:33:25.530
to moving back toward women,
young women, those are children,

00:33:25.530 --> 00:33:31.700
and was it easy or was it just
kind of what you writers do?

00:33:31.700 --> 00:33:34.050
&gt;&gt; Claire Messud: Well, I think,
I mean, interestingly, in my case,

00:33:34.050 --> 00:33:36.920
you know, somebody said to me,
how did you do all the research

00:33:36.920 --> 00:33:38.380
about the pop songs and stuff?

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:41.300
And I was like, well, I drive my
kids everywhere, so, you know,

00:33:41.300 --> 00:33:44.120
it's just what they insist
on putting on the radio.

00:33:44.120 --> 00:33:50.270
So I think in some ways, it
isn't really the same, it isn't--

00:33:50.270 --> 00:33:53.830
just because of the nature of
my daily life, it wasn't a move

00:33:53.830 --> 00:33:56.040
like suddenly trying
to write something set

00:33:56.040 --> 00:34:00.560
in 1850 in Japan, you know?

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:02.670
I'm a woman in midlife.

00:34:02.670 --> 00:34:04.750
I have a daughter who's a teenager.

00:34:04.750 --> 00:34:08.400
They're very different experiences.

00:34:08.400 --> 00:34:12.520
And the experiences of my own
and my daughter's experiences are

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:16.560
in no way those of any of the
characters in either novel.

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:23.700
But just as a sort of [inaudible]
or world, it didn't feel

00:34:23.700 --> 00:34:26.370
like such a big leap in that case.

00:34:26.370 --> 00:34:29.190
Thank you.

00:34:29.190 --> 00:34:34.740
&gt;&gt; Yeah, so you had
mentioned that the story upon

00:34:34.740 --> 00:34:39.020 position:56%
which The Burning Girl was based on,
you know, you had been carrying it

00:34:39.020 --> 00:34:41.740
in your head for a long time.

00:34:41.740 --> 00:34:43.950
I'm sure you've been carrying
a lot of other stories,

00:34:43.950 --> 00:34:46.900
even before you wrote
Emperor's Children.

00:34:46.900 --> 00:34:54.570 position:56%
What was it that made you say, okay,
now is the time to choose this story

00:34:54.570 --> 00:34:57.880
over everything else in your
head, now is the time to put this

00:34:57.880 --> 00:35:02.400
on paper, to make that commitment?

00:35:02.400 --> 00:35:05.840
&gt;&gt; Claire Messud: And
yes, I think it was--

00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:08.950
the magpie thing works
up to a point,

00:35:08.950 --> 00:35:12.880
and then it's almost more
than a composting thing.

00:35:12.880 --> 00:35:16.210
So it's like you put in the
eggshells and you put in the,

00:35:16.210 --> 00:35:21.990
you know, peelings, and then
at some point, a shoot comes up

00:35:21.990 --> 00:35:23.660
and something is growing.

00:35:23.660 --> 00:35:27.890
And I think it was really that
sense, that I had had this,

00:35:27.890 --> 00:35:30.910
and I didn't quite know
where to go with it.

00:35:30.910 --> 00:35:36.390
And then watching our kids go
through this time, and as I said,

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:38.210
not just our daughter
and son, but our nieces

00:35:38.210 --> 00:35:40.600
and nephews watching
these experiences,

00:35:40.600 --> 00:35:44.110
it suddenly seemed
pressing and urgent in a way

00:35:44.110 --> 00:35:47.520
that connected to this story.

00:35:47.520 --> 00:35:53.150
And I guess it sounds sort of
abstract, but I really do believe

00:35:53.150 --> 00:35:55.860
that this time and these
middle school years,

00:35:55.860 --> 00:35:59.630
it's when we're forged as people.

00:35:59.630 --> 00:36:04.380
It's when whatever happens in those
years marks us for good or ill

00:36:04.380 --> 00:36:07.700
and shapes who we will
become, et cetera.

00:36:07.700 --> 00:36:10.240
I always say, if you're having
trouble with any, you know,

00:36:10.240 --> 00:36:11.540
if you're having trouble
with a person,

00:36:11.540 --> 00:36:13.570
just picture them in
seventh grade, right?

00:36:13.570 --> 00:36:15.970
And suddenly everything
becomes clear, right?

00:36:15.970 --> 00:36:20.600
I mean, picture say the leader of
our country, picture middle school,

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:26.200
like suddenly many things
become clear, right?

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:30.070
So I think having those
years up close in front of me

00:36:30.070 --> 00:36:33.950
and feeling the urgency
of them was part of it.

00:36:33.950 --> 00:36:35.250
&gt;&gt; Thanks very much.

00:36:35.250 --> 00:36:37.550
&gt;&gt; Claire Messud: Thank you.

00:36:40.300 --> 00:36:46.650
&gt;&gt; Yeah, with the courage born
of ignorance, I see so much.

00:36:46.650 --> 00:36:52.330
I was recently at a book
sale at a thrift store,

00:36:52.330 --> 00:36:56.340
and there were just
racks and racks and racks

00:36:56.340 --> 00:37:01.270
of dystopian novels aimed at--

00:37:01.270 --> 00:37:07.540
I just would like to pitch
out the idea that the universe

00:37:07.540 --> 00:37:14.540
in which we live is enough of a
dystopia, and we're robbing kids

00:37:14.540 --> 00:37:17.320
of the ability to figure
out what's going on now

00:37:17.320 --> 00:37:19.940
by projecting what's
going into the future.

00:37:19.940 --> 00:37:22.920
Would you care to comment on that?

00:37:22.920 --> 00:37:24.220
&gt;&gt; Claire Messud: Yes, sir.

00:37:24.220 --> 00:37:26.740
So if everybody heard the
question or the comment,

00:37:26.740 --> 00:37:30.220
it was about the vast
range of dystopian fictions

00:37:30.220 --> 00:37:37.510 position:56%
that are available in book form and
in other forms also for young people

00:37:37.510 --> 00:37:44.700
to read, and to not be focusing
on our dystopian reality.

00:37:44.700 --> 00:37:49.970
You know, I'm a reader who
always wants to be in reality.

00:37:49.970 --> 00:37:52.830
I'm not somebody for whom fantasy--

00:37:52.830 --> 00:37:54.870
there are some fantasy
books that I love,

00:37:54.870 --> 00:38:00.970
but it's not my primary
mode as a reader.

00:38:00.970 --> 00:38:05.250
And so I have to take
it from people I know

00:38:05.250 --> 00:38:09.150
for whom it is the primary
mode, that sometimes it's almost

00:38:09.150 --> 00:38:14.850
like Glenn Gould playing the piano
and putting on the vacuum cleaner.

00:38:14.850 --> 00:38:16.150
You know, he used to do that.

00:38:16.150 --> 00:38:17.450
And it helped him.

00:38:17.450 --> 00:38:18.890
He said it helped him hear better.

00:38:18.890 --> 00:38:22.440
I think there are some readers
for whom all of the issues

00:38:22.440 --> 00:38:28.580 position:56%
of our actual society are set in
better relief in an imaginary world,

00:38:28.580 --> 00:38:33.970
that they actually, they can
actually see them more clearly

00:38:33.970 --> 00:38:37.590
if they're set in an
imaginary time and place.

00:38:37.590 --> 00:38:38.890
That's not the case for me.

00:38:38.890 --> 00:38:40.730
So I'm with you.

00:38:40.730 --> 00:38:44.600 position:56%
I feel that will are so many stories
to tell right here right now.

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:46.510
So thank you, sir.

00:38:46.510 --> 00:38:47.810
And I think that will be the--

00:38:47.810 --> 00:38:50.860
this will be the last
question, I imagine.

00:38:50.860 --> 00:38:52.160
Yes, sir?

00:38:52.160 --> 00:38:55.010
&gt;&gt; You have written about
two middle school girls.

00:38:55.010 --> 00:38:59.810
Would you posit that their
experience and your conclusions

00:38:59.810 --> 00:39:04.950
that you draw from it are very
different from middle school boys?

00:39:04.950 --> 00:39:12.400
&gt;&gt; Claire Messud: You know, it's
a really interesting question.

00:39:12.400 --> 00:39:17.950
I think to which my
answer would be yes and no.

00:39:17.950 --> 00:39:19.250
Unhelpfully.

00:39:19.250 --> 00:39:25.780
I think in some ways it
depends on the kids, right?

00:39:25.780 --> 00:39:29.420
It depends so much on the
individual and the temperament

00:39:29.420 --> 00:39:32.550
and the dynamics between
individual kids.

00:39:32.550 --> 00:39:37.450
And as a rule, as a rule, you could
say maybe it's a little different

00:39:37.450 --> 00:39:38.750
for boys than girls.

00:39:38.750 --> 00:39:40.740
Although I don't know if there's
anyone here who's read David

00:39:40.740 --> 00:39:42.670 position:56%
Mitchell, the author of Cloud Atlas,

00:39:42.670 --> 00:39:44.630
wrote a wonderful book
called Black Swan Green,

00:39:44.630 --> 00:39:50.210
which is about adolescent boys,
interactions that read very--

00:39:50.210 --> 00:39:54.690 position:56%
when I read it, it struck me as very
familiar from my girl experience.

00:39:54.690 --> 00:40:02.770
And so I think it really,
it depends.

00:40:02.770 --> 00:40:09.420
I'd say as a writer, I'm a
great believer in character.

00:40:09.420 --> 00:40:10.810
I have many interests.

00:40:10.810 --> 00:40:15.050
Language, the music of language,
metaphor, da da da da da.

00:40:15.050 --> 00:40:17.520
But when I'm really interested
in, the bottom line, is people,

00:40:17.520 --> 00:40:19.360
and how people are in the world,

00:40:19.360 --> 00:40:21.590
who makes us who we
are and how we behave.

00:40:21.590 --> 00:40:26.740
And so I think the groundedness
of each person in their place,

00:40:26.740 --> 00:40:31.370
in their time, in their
dynamic, is what makes the story.

00:40:31.370 --> 00:40:37.210
And gender is some small part of
that, but not the whole thing.

00:40:37.210 --> 00:40:39.370
Thank you.

